The Technical Exchange tour included visits to key institutions, which are directly responsible for monitoring climate and developing / implementing protocols to respond to any foreseeable critical or extreme event in the context of floods. The following presents the main findings from the mission in the context of flood management and the potential contributions to the InterAguas Project:  

Â·	The visit to the National Crises Coordination Center presented the team with state of the art technologies used for crises coordination, but more importantly how national organizations are arranged and represented whenever events occur that can hamper or threat the country and its citizens. The Center has to control data collection, information sharing and decision-making not only when a natural hazard triggers a possible disaster, but also during man-made disasters (e.g. terrorism);
Â·	Key national projects such as the âRoom for the Riverâ and comprehensive actions to enable delta living (note that The Netherlands is a country with a vast area located in a delta plain). Both projects have shown great coordination capability among national, regional and local authorities as well as key participation from the communities in order to ensure the successful accomplishment of project objectives; 
Â·	A remarkable experience can be highlighted by the effectiveness and representation of local communities in water / flood management project through the Water Boards. These local representations are of great importance to align national and local interests so actions towards water and flood management can be better planned and implemented;
Â·	A visit to Deltares was conducted and has shown how a partially public funded institution can be catalytic in conducting research and developing technologies. Deltares is a world renowned institution with half of its funds from the National Government and half from its international projects. It is worth noting that the institution is required to develop projects of national interest in order to receive the domestic funds;
Â·	Presentations on the Brazilian State initiatives and the World Bank office in Brazil in Disaster Risk Management were delivered to Dutch representatives so a better context of the challenges in Brazil and possible activities could be discussed. This has been key for the final activity planned to take place on Oct 8th and 9th (see next section);
Â·	The National Flood Forecasting Center from the Ministry of Infrastructure and Environment (Rijkswaterstaat) was visited at the Lelystad complex. Among the different technologies observed, it can be highlighted the international cooperation with neighbor countries as the management of water resources implies the need to consider watersheds and not geo-political boundaries; and
Â·	The final activity was the workshop on inter institutional cooperation (Dutch and Brazilian organization and methods) elaboration of swimming lanes method and preparation for follow-up activity in Brazil (described in the next section).

